ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Does your child currently experience any tics, both motor and/or vocal?
Notes: 0= No; 1= Yes

ElementDescription: Eye blinking: Did your child experienced the tic over the past week?
Notes: 0= No; 1= Yes

ElementDescription: Eye Blinking frequency: Did the tic occur over the past week?
Notes: 1= Constant, almost all the time during the day; 2= Hourly, at least once per hour; 3= Daily, at least several times per day; 4= Weekly, just a few times or less

ElementDescription: Eye Blinking intensity: Did the tic appear to you during the past week?
Notes: 1= Very mild, like a weak twitch; 2= Tic that are obviously noticeable to others; 3= Forceful tic that would be very noticeable to others and may even be painful; 4= Severe tic, a much more forceful tic that is very noticeable to others and painful
